      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In a debate setting, the argument prioritizing life and safety is often perceived as having a stronger moral imperative, as the right to life is widely considered a fundamental, inalienable human right. You can argue that national borders are legal constructs, whereas the threat of death or torture is a concrete, immediate moral crisis. Therefore, the ethical weight of preventing human suffering and death generally outweighs the administrative concerns of border enforcement.",
      "source": "target",
